  "prompt": "As an individual, can I get a patent for my ideas?",
  "response": "To get a patent, your idea must meet certain criteria:\n\n1. Patentability Requirements:\n- Must be novel (new)\n- Must be non-obvious\n- Must have practical utility\n- Must be a specific process, machine, manufacture, or composition of matter\n\n2. Types of Patentable Ideas:\n- Inventions\n- Technological innovations\n- Unique processes or methods\n- Specific machine designs\n- Software algorithms\n\n3. Steps to Patent an Idea:\n- Conduct a thorough patent search\n- Document your invention in detail\n- Prepare a patent application\n- File with the United States Patent and Trademark Office (USPTO)\n- Pay required fees\n- Undergo examination process\n\n4. Important Considerations:\n- Provisional patents offer temporary protection\n- Full patents are expensive and complex\n- Legal assistance is often recommended\n- Patents last 20 years from filing date\n\n5. What Cannot Be Patented:\n- Abstract ideas\n- Natural phenomena\n- Laws of nature\n- Pure mathematical algorithms\n- Purely aesthetic designs\n\n6. Costs:\n- Professional patent applications can cost $5,000-$15,000\n- Government filing fees range $300-$700\n\nConsulting an intellectual property attorney can help navigate the patent process effectively.",
